3 WHEREAS, during the 1910-1911 school year, a small group of Black
4 students at Indiana University, realizing that they had no part in the
5 university's social life, decided that a Greek-letter fraternity would do
6 much to fill the missing link in their college existence, particularly as two
7 (2) members of this group had previously attended Howard University in
8 Washington, D.C., home of the only national historically Black Greek-letter
9 fraternity then in existence; and
10
11 WHEREAS, the founding members of Kappa Alpha Psi Fraternity, Inc., were
12 God-fearing and serious-minded young men with the imagination, ambition,
13 courage, and determination to defy custom in pursuit of a college education
14 and career, and they decided that their fraternity would be more than a
15 social organization, and would instead be founded upon the concept of
16 achievement; and
17
18 WHEREAS, Kappa Alpha Psi Fraternity, Inc., is the second-oldest
19 existing collegiate historically Black Greek-letter fraternity, and its
20 members are proud that its Constitution has never contained any clause that
21 excludes a man from membership because of his color, creed, or national
22 origin; and
23
24 WHEREAS, local chapters of Kappa Alpha Psi Fraternity, Inc.,
25 participate in community outreach activities to feed the homeless, provide
26 scholarships to young people matriculating to college, serve as mentors to
27 young men, participate in blood drives, and serve as hosts of seminars for
28 public health awareness, and the fraternity has also provided summer
29 enrichment camps and over one million dollars ($1,000,000) in funds for St.
30 Jude Children's Research Hospital; and
31
32 WHEREAS, members of Kappa Alpha Psi Fraternity, Inc., have also
33 answered the call to service by proudly serving in the United States Armed
34 Forces since World War I and raising funds to assist those in need following
35 natural disasters worldwide; and
